		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Foil Theory<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.51)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058'>Jonathan "Carny" brown</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=7058&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> We’ve all seen the guy. He walks into the gaming store and the first thing he says is “anyone got any tight foils?”. That’s right, the foil guy. This is the guy who, whether they admit it or not, everyone is envious of. He has foils, In multiple, of every card in the game. His deck is shiny enough to blind a cast member of 90210(cause they wear shades!) and his trade list says “I don’t need ANYTHING you have, but you want EVERYTHING I have”. This article will examine the things that make foils SOOOO desirable to players, collectors and little children. Okay, not so much the little children, cause obviously they just like to look at them. Hopefully it will be funny, informative and maybe it’ll help some of us to understand that poor, tortured soul who has more money than he knows what to do with.<br />
<br />
STATUS<br />
<br />
Well, first of all it is more than obvious that Foils are a symbol of status in the gaming world. I mean honestly, how many players with all foil decks have you seen NOT at the top tables of tournaments? Granted, there always be a few players with more money than skill, but usually the person who is willing to spend all that time trading for 4 Foil Troop of Uruks, Savageries and Sarumans has at least better than average card flopping skills. Now, don’t think for a minute that I mean that only foiled decks can be successful. It is actually quite the opposite, most players that play well spend more time thinking about playing the game than trading for foil Chinese Goblin Armories, I just mean that to some, having foils is a symbol of status. I myself take great pride in having an all foil site path, but I harbor no hope of EVER having enough money or time to foil the rest of my deck. I guess in summary foils can bring to some players imagined status, where none is deserved.<br />
<br />
DISTRACTION<br />
<br />
My favorite tactic when playing cards is to hold up a foil one ring and quickly, while my opponent is choking on their drool, flip through their deck and see what shadow culture they are playing, replacing there deck almost immediately after putting all the minions on the bottom of the deck and all the support cards on top. Okay, while that’s not exactly what I mean by distraction, foils can be a quite effective one, especially against players who are already afraid of you. Not that I am any big name in the gaming world, but I know for a fact that a foil starting fellowship immediately gets an opponent who hasn’t faced you before worried about their first fellowship turn. I can’t explain why, but people see foil mains and they assume you know what you are doing. For all they know, you are a CHAMP who won all those foils by winning every tournament you went to, when in all actuality, you are a lucky scrub who pulled foil Arwen and foil Legolas in the same booster pack your Grandmother bought you for Easter. This goes back to the status elements, but it can cause your opponents to play stupidly, worrying about plays they never would have second guessed and winning you games easily that you might have struggled through, or even lost. Granted, this won’t work on friends, or on people who KNOW they’re good, but it can give you the edge on opponents you don’t have a clue about. <br />
<br />
LOVE LIFE<br />
<br />
Okay, well this is less about playing and more about using foils to help your significant other understand your gaming disease. Never underestimate the power of a shiny, sweaty Viggo Mortenson or Orlando Bloom to convince your girl-friend, or potential girl-friend, that theres less wrong with you than there really is. Fortunatly for me, it hasn’t been a problem , as I have been able to pass the love of card games, and hobbits, to the love of my life, but to all of you who haven’t been as lucky: FOIL Aragorn wins the argument! That’s all I have to say, cause I don’t wanna get into too much trouble. <br />
<br />
PROFITABILITY<br />
<br />
This is for those of you who don’t understand WHY some of us go Ape-S*** over cards that have been dramatically touched up with “foil”. You guys don’t have a clue why we’ll trade TONS of great, playable rares for a crappy card that happens to look cool when you hold it in the light. All I can say to you guys is simply this: “We like the way they look!” <br />
So, for you guys who DON’T give a crap about foils, profit from it. I once saw a guy trade 2 Regular Flaming Brands, 2 Foil Sites, and 3 SWCCG cards that were very desirable(AI’s of Palpatine, Amidala and Sidious) for ONE FOIL FLAMING BRAND. I mean, that’s a little extreme even in MY eyes. Basically, what I am trying to say is, don’t try to understand it, just benefit from it.<br />
<br />
GAMEPLAY<br />
<br />
Some cards just seem to play better if they are foil. I know that this has no true basis in reality, but for some reason, I think it is true. I have a foils Sting that I have not had for very long. Ever since I got it, I seem to draw Sting at exactly the right moment. Before I got Sting in Foil, I never seemed to have it when I needed it, and whether or not it has anything to do with the shiny stuff on the card, the foil Sting likes to be in play A LOT more than my non-foil sting. Perhaps this is because of the inherent vanity contained in all foils. Perhaps it is because the foil cards are thicker, and they get shuffled to the top of the deck, or perhaps I am just insane, but either way, foil cards play better!<br />
<br />
Well, that’s about all I can think of right now to help understand foils and the people who lust after them. I hope this has not been too much of a waste of time, I just don’t really have anything better to do. I know that anyone who has met Andy McClure or Will Cruise will identify with this article, and I am more than sure that every local gaming group has a “Foil Guy”, cause, scarily enough, I think I am him. Thanks for reading, and please include any extra “Foil Theories” in the reviews, or just say “ You are Wrong” or “This was stupid” or “ this belongs on the buzz board” like everyone else. Later!<br />
<br />
The Carny<br />
